hints_latex:
The eigenvectors are the non-trivial vectors that satisfy

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}(A-\lambda{}I)\mathbf{x}=\mathbf{0}.
\end{align*}

Setting the determinant to be zero (when finding the eigenvalues) is
what makes such vectors possible.

Calculate vectors $\displaystyle x$ and $\displaystyle y$ which satisfy

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} -1-\lambda_1 & -2 \\ 2 & -1 - \lambda_1\end{pmatrix}x = 0
\end{align*}
and

\begin{align*}
\begin{pmatrix} -1-\lambda_2 & -2 \\ 2 & -1 - \lambda_2\end{pmatrix}y = 0
\end{align*}

These correspond to the two eigenvalues from
{part
(a)}.

statement_latex:
Consider the 2 x 2 system of differential equations

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}'(t)=\begin{bmatrix}
-1  &  -2\\
2  &  -1
\end{bmatrix} \mathbf{x}(t)
\end{align*}

where $\mathbf{x}(t)=\begin{bmatrix}x_1(t)\\x_2(t)\end{bmatrix}$ is the
vector of unknown functions.

Find the corresponding eigenvectors.
